"Gordon J.E., Dvorák I.J., Jonasson C., Josefsson M., Kociánová M., Thompson D.B.A.","Geo-ecology and management of sensitive montane landscapes",2002,"Geografiska Annaler, Series A: Physical Geography","84","3-4",,"193","203",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0036970249&partnerID=40&md5=98393135adb131ed3037c02db1a7dfe5","Scottish Natural Heritage, 2 Anderson Place, Edinburgh EH6 5NP, United Kingdom; Krkonose Natl. Park Administration, Dobrovsḱeho 3, Vrchlabí 543 01, Czech Republic; Abisko Scientific Research Station, Abisko, Sweden; Swedish Envrn. Protection Agency, Uppsala, Sweden","Gordon, J.E., Scottish Natural Heritage, 2 Anderson Place, Edinburgh EH6 5NP, United Kingdom; Dvorák, I.J., Krkonose Natl. Park Administration, Dobrovsḱeho 3, Vrchlabí 543 01, Czech Republic; Jonasson, C., Abisko Scientific Research Station, Abisko, Sweden; Josefsson, M., Swedish Envrn. Protection Agency, Uppsala, Sweden; Kociánová, M., Krkonose Natl. Park Administration, Dobrovsḱeho 3, Vrchlabí 543 01, Czech Republic; Thompson, D.B.A., Scottish Natural Heritage, 2 Anderson Place, Edinburgh EH6 5NP, United Kingdom","Montane (alpine) areas are generally of high value for nature conservation. Such environments and the habitats they support are dynamic and often fragile. They are vulnerable to disturbance from a range of human activities and are responsive to climate changes over short and long timescales. Biodiversity and conservation values are closely linked to geological history, geomorphological processes and soils, and it is crucial that management systems are based on understanding these links. There are many similarities between the Cairngorm Mountains (Scotland), the Giant Mountains (Czech Republic) and Abisko Mountains (Sweden) in terms of geology, geomorphology, ecology, links with biodiversity and high conservation importance. Comparable pressures and management issues involve, to varying degrees, a history of human use and impacts from deforestation, pasturing, grazing, recreation and atmospheric pollution. Landscape change therefore involves a complex interplay between natural and anthropogenic factors. Managing such change requires better understanding of the geo-ecological processes involved and the factors that determine landscape sensitivity. This is illustrated through a simple framework and examples from the three areas. Comparison of landscape sensitivity between similar montane areas. but in different geographic locations and climatic environments, should allow more informed management planning and a precautionary approach in advance of further changes in human activity and from predicted global warming scenarios.",,"alpine environment; environmental management; geomorphology; human activity; landscape change; nature conservation; Czech Republic; Sweden; United Kingdom",,,,,,"Allard, A., Ihse, M., Nordberg, M.-L., (1998) Vegetation Changes in the Mountains. Method Study in the Northern Mountains With the Help of Infared Aerial Photographs and Satellite Scenes, , University of Stockholm Department of Physical Geography Research Report, No. 109, 47 p. (in Swedish); Bäck, L., Bäck, E., The effects of a road construction-Highway 98 between Kiruna and Riksgränsen (1986) Acta Universitatis Upsaliensis, 52. , Series C; Bäck, L., Jonasson, C., (1998) Environmental Impact Assessments of the Highway Between Kiruna and Riksgränsen, , Forskningsrapporter från Kulturgeografiska Institutionen, Uppsala Universitet. No. 109, 126 p. (in Swedish); Bäck, L., Jonasson, C., The Kiruna-Narvik road and its impact on the environment and on recreational land use (1998) Ambio, 27, pp. 345-350; Bäck, L., Josefsson, M., Strömquist, L., (1989) Land Capability, Recreational Land-Use and Conservation Strategies in a Sensitive Mountain Environment. A Method Study from the Kiruna Mountains, , Sweden. Uppsala Universitet Naturgeografiska Institutionen. UNGI Rapport, No. 73, 30 p; Bäck, L., Jonasson, C., Strömquist, L., (1990) Environmental 